HEADWORD: Podium
<hw>Po"di*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Podia</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/, dim. of <?/,
<?/, foot. See <er>Pew</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld>
<def>A low wall, serving as a foundation, a substructure, or a terrace
wall.</def> It is especially employed by arch⟦ae⟧ologists in two senses:
<sd>(a)</sd> <def>The dwarf wall surrounding the arena of an
amphitheater, from the top of which the seats began.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>The masonry under the stylobate of a temple, sometimes a mere
foundation, sometimes containing chambers.</def> See <xex>Illust.</xex>
of <er>Column</er>.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The foot.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Podley</ent>⟦br⟧
